# Spec-First, Eval-Driven Development with Morph

This project uses Morph for behavioral version control. The **eval suite is
the canonical specification** — every commit is gated against the union of
acceptance cases registered in the repo's default `EvalSuite`. Unit tests
are an implementation detail; the acceptance case is the contract.

To feed this system, work spec-first.

## Workflow

1. **Write the acceptance case before the code.**
   - User-visible behavior → a YAML spec (see this project's spec
     directory) where each top-level entry is one case.
   - End-to-end flows → a cucumber `.feature`. Each `Scenario:` becomes one
     case.

   The spec describes behavior in terms a human reviewer can audit, not
   implementation details.

2. **Register it.** Add the case to the default eval suite:

   ```bash
   morph eval add-case path/to/spec.yaml
   morph eval suite-show           # sanity-check what's registered
   ```

   The first call also wires the suite to `policy.default_eval_suite`, so
   future commits inherit it automatically.

3. **Watch it fail.** Run the eval suite via `morph eval run`. This shells
   out to your test command, captures stdout, parses cargo / pytest /
   vitest / jest / go output, and writes a metric-bearing `Run` linked to
   HEAD. A failure is the spec doing its job:

   ```bash
   morph eval run -- cargo test --workspace
   ```

4. **Implement until it goes green.** Iterate with `morph eval run`. Unit
   tests inside `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` (or the language equivalent) are
   useful — but they're an implementation detail. The merge gate only sees
   the suite.

5. **Commit from the recorded run.**

   ```bash
   morph eval run -- cargo test --workspace
   # Copy the printed run hash, then:
   morph commit -m "<feature>" \
     --from-run <hash> \
     --new-cases <case_id_a>,<case_id_b>
   ```

   `--from-run` attaches the run's metrics as the commit's
   `observed_metrics`, so the merge gate has evidence. `--new-cases`
   records which acceptance cases this commit *introduced*; merge plans
   surface that provenance across branches.

   If repo policy requires metrics (the `morph init` default), an
   empty-metrics commit is rejected. `--allow-empty-metrics` is an audited
   escape hatch, not a default.

## Self-check at any time

- `morph_status` returns an `Evidence:` block: HEAD metrics, default suite
  case count, recent runs, and working-tree freshness.
- `morph_eval_gaps` returns a structured list of gaps —
  `empty_head_metrics`, `empty_default_suite`, `no_recent_run`. If it
  returns anything non-empty, you're not done.

## Why this matters

A commit without metrics is just a file snapshot. A commit *with* metrics
attached to an acceptance case is a behavioral certificate. Morph merges
require the merged program to dominate both parents on every registered
metric — that comparison is only possible when each branch carries cases
and metric-bearing runs.

Tests aren't a CI gate, and unit tests aren't the primary artifact. The
acceptance case is. Treat it that way and Morph's behavioral merges work
the way they're supposed to.
